 Technical Maintenance Report (Q4OS System / TDE Interface)

Prepared by: Technical Support Unit - AbbesTechTn
Contact: abbes.tech.tn@gmail.com
Target Device: Toshiba Satellite L30-105 (RAM 2GB / 32-bit)
 1. Summary of Technical Obstacles
The device faced a series of software-related challenges that hindered the benefits of the mechanical repairs performed on the optical disc drive:
 Network Obstacle: Inability to access official repositories (Debian Repos).
 Graphics Obstacle: Video player crashes (Segmentation Fault).
 Encryption Obstacle: Refusal to read protected discs and region code mismatch (Region Code).
 Input Obstacle: Scattered keyboard layout and absence of an on-screen keyboard.
2. Practical Procedures & Terminal Commands
Phase I: Fixing Repository Connection (Fix APT Repos)
 Problem: System failure to resolve download links due to IPv6 conflicts.
 Procedure: Forcing the system to use the stable IPv4 protocol.
 Commands:

```
Create a configuration file to force IPv4

echo 'Acquire::ForceIPv4 "true";' | sudo tee /etc/apt/apt.conf.d/99force-ipv4

 Update the repository list to ensure successful connection

sudo apt update

```
Phase II: Installing Graphic Drivers
 Problem: Missing firmware files for the integrated
 ATI Radeon card, causing system freezes during movie playback.
 Procedure: Installing "Non-free" packages to support hardware acceleration.
 Commands:

```
 Install essential drivers and graphics acceleration libraries

sudo apt install firmware-linux-nonfree libgl1-mesa-dri xserver-xorg-video-ati

```
Phase III: Media & Disc Drive Activation (DVD & Decryption)
 Problem: Original discs are encrypted and fail to run due to disc drive region mismatch.
 Procedure: Setting the drive region to (Region 2 - Tunisia/Europe) and installing decryption libraries.
 Commands:

```
1. Set the drive region (Select "2" when prompted)

sudo apt install regionset && sudo regionset /dev/sr0

 2. Install the library for decrypting protected movies

sudo apt install libdvd-pkg && sudo dpkg-reconfigure libdvd-pkg

```
Phase IV: Configuring Input Tools (Keyboard & On-Screen)
 Problem: Mismatch between physical keys and typed characters; need for a virtual keyboard.
 Procedure: Adding 
AZERTY/AR layouts and installing the Onboard software.
 Commands:

```
 1. Install the On-Screen Keyboard

sudo apt install onboard

 2. Quick command to set French layout (AZERTY) immediately

setxkbmap fr

3. Command to merge Arabic and French with Alt+Shift toggle

setxkbmap -layout "fr,ar" -option "grp:alt_shift_toggle"

```
3. Technical Recommendations for Stable Operation (Best Practices)
Given the limited hardware specifications (2GB RAM), the following protocol must be followed to ensure smooth performance:
 1. Certified Player: Use
 SMPlayer instead of VLC; it consumes fewer resources and interacts directly with the path /dev/sr0.
 2. Memory Management: 
Close the web browser completely when playing movies to free up RAM for the processor.
 3. Automatic Startup: Add the Onboard program to the 
Autostart list in the
 TDE Control Center to ensure it appears upon login.
 Final Device Status
> "The device is now in full operational status. The mechanical drive is supported by decrypted software, graphics drivers are stable, and the input interface is configured for professional use."
